by bike, as they are so common and a preferred method of transportation across the island. There is only one road and a series of cross streets, so it is actually one of the safest places I have ever biked. Being bored and anxious (aka bored-ansy) also plays a part here, but as I rode further up and down the town, I realized that I was actually getting exercise and seeing parts (aka fringe of town) I would have never witnessed had I been driving or walking. Approximately one hour later I was back at the hotel, hungry and ready to attack the grocery list.

For dinner we were poised to Chicken with Rice and Beans, use as many common words as possible, but with Mango Sauce. The everyday condiment of Cuba has both Mango and Ketchup as a base or flavors. With the mandate stuck in my mind, I started throwing it on the pieces of chicken that resembled a slight diaphragm and squeezed it on the display of cooked rice I was serving and banging the salsa on the table the next to my hubby. “Fuere con mango!” I commanded, realizing that only a distant relative of a mildly familiar four letter word spelled “mango” and a literal translation of “be with” was used in this context of the sauce.
